This paper is primarily focused on the navigation of robots in social environments, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). Additionally, the paper draws on psychological research to inform the design of the navigation algorithm, which suggests a potential fit for the human-computer interaction (cs.HC) category. The use of data-driven algorithms and machine learning techniques to optimize robot behavior also suggests a potential fit for the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) category. The paper also discusses the use of computer vision techniques to evaluate the effectiveness of the navigation algorithm, which suggests a potential fit for the computer vision (cs.CV) category. Finally, the paper discusses the social implications of robot behavior and the potential for robots to elicit emotional reactions from humans, which suggests a potential fit for the social and information sciences (cs.SI) category.
